04147nam a22006735i 9781442675810DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182005onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426758107 a10.3138/97814426758102doi  a(DE-B1597)497206  a(OCoLC)1078918434  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHD8108.5.A2 7aSOC0070002bisacsh04a331.6/209712221 aSharma, Nandita, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHome Economics :bNationalism and the Making of ‘Migrant Workers’ in Canada /cNandita Sharma. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2018] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (220 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tForeword -- t1. Home(lessness) and the Naturalization of ‘Difference’ -- t2. Globalization and the Story of National Sovereignty -- t3. Imagined States: The Ideology of ‘National Society’ -- t4. Canadian Parliamentary Discourse and the Making of ‘Migrant Workers’ -- t5. Canada’s Non-Immigrant Employment Authorization Program (NIEAP): The Social Organization of Unfreedom for ‘Migrant Workers’ -- t6. Rejecting Global Apartheid: An Essay on the Refusal of ‘Difference’ -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA massive shift has taken place in Canadian immigration policy since the 1970s: the majority of migrants no longer enter as permanent residents but as temporary migrant workers. In Home Economics, Nandita Sharma shows how Canadian policies on citizenship and immigration contribute to the entrenchment of a system of apartheid where those categorized as ‘migrant workers’ live, work, pay taxes and sometimes die in Canada but are subordinated to a legal regime that renders them as perennial outsiders to nationalized Canadian society.In calling for a ‘no borders’ policy in Canada, Sharma argues that it is the acceptance of nationalist formulations of ‘home’ informed by racialized and gendered relations that contribute to the neo-liberal restructuring of the labour market in Canada. She exposes the ideological character of Canadian border control policies which, rather than preventing people from getting in, actually work to restrict their rights once within Canada. Home Economics is an urgent and much-needed reminder that in today’s world of growing displacement and unprecedented levels of international migration, society must pay careful attention to how nationalist ideologies construct ‘homelands’ that essentially leave the vast majority of the world’s migrant peoples homeless.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCapitalism. 0aForeign workersxGovernment policyzCanada. 0aGlobalization. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267581040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442675810423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442675810.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK